default4.4
default&#xa0;
defaultWe have over 18,000 service charge payers. All are affected in some way by the introduction of Universal Credit.  
defaultNegative implications could affect us as landlords in two ways
default: 
defaultCurrent legisla
defaulttion allows us to depreciate the cost of
default repairs and replacement of lifts
default. 
defaultUnder revised 
defaultDWP guidance
default this won’t continue to happen.
default The impact
default means a potential annual loss of 
default£550,000
default. Service charges could be increased to cover this, but with many resid
defaultents affected by welfare changes, ultimately we’ll have to cover the loss through bad debt provision. This has
default an adverse effect on our business plan and therefore our ability to build new homes. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn some flats, particularly high rise we have responsibility for window cleaning. DWP guidance says we will not be able to charge for cleaning relating to ground floor flats. 
defaultSignificant timely and costly work has to be undertaken for us to 
defaultchange all lega
defaultl agreements with residents’
default. Without this residents will
default be paying for 
defaultservices they don’t receive.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe guidance also fails to take account of the legal agreements with tenants, including leaseholders. These constrain the options available to both us
default and the tenant. Apportionments for charges are set out in leases and tenancy agreements.  It’s a contract to pay us charges due. So, those in flats will have to make their Universal Credit payment stretch further to cover the cost of non eligible charges 
defaultwhich they have no choice but to receive.
default Ultimately as a landlord we’ll be at a financial loss as bad debt is incurred.
