default5.7
defaultWe’ve won national customer service awards demonstrating how passionate we are about our service
default to vulnerable clients in TA
default. 
default&#xa0;
default Financially it’s becoming more difficult to provide the service across all 18 areas. The changes to housing costs within the wel
defaultfare system remain a huge concern to the future of us being able to house vulnerable homeless clients.
defaultThe Government are introducing direct payments within universal credit. The main aim is to empower residents to manage money, ensuring they understand ho
defaultw working families budget when receiving a monthly salary. The Government tell us this will be a cost neutral exercise for them. What they haven’t considered is the full impact direct payments will have. Even though Government recognise Universal Credit mu
defaultst be designed to protect the financial position of landlords, d
defaultirect payment to tenants still means landlords will have to take unacceptable risks on collecting rent. Many landlords will not take that risk, leading to less supply in the private rented 
defaultsec
defaulttor and a higher B&amp;B bill/ cost to public purse. 
defaultConcern has already been stressed by many landlords that low income or vulnerable families will not pay rent.
default No families in temporary accommodation have been included in the UC pilots.
default If this happens ultimately these families will end up being evicted. As local authorities have a duty to find shelter for homeless families, their only option will be to place them in unsuitable and expensive B&amp;B. 
default&#xa0;
defaultMany aspects of Welfare reform make lea
defaultsing temporary accommodation from the private sector no longer a financial viable option for many registered social landlords. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe supply of good quality temporary accommodation is reducing, especially in London &amp; the South where there’s a buoyant private
default rental market. 
default&#xa0;
defaultThe
default direct payment element 
defaultwill not make 
defaultthe welfare reform policy cost neutral. Instead it will increase LA spend through 
defaultDiscretionary Housing Payments (
defaultDHP
default) 
defaultor the general fund.
default 
defaultIf tenants do not pay their rent registered social landlo
defaultrds will incur higher bad debt. This will ultimately affect our credit scoring and ability to borrow/self fund in an environment where grant funding to build new affordable homes is 
defaultdisappearing. The
default end result is registered social landlords will not build
default much needed new homes, holding back the recovery of the economy even further.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultWe want to continue to provide this service which our L
defaultA
default partners value. But proposed changes to how TA is funded are making it increasingly difficult for us to retain lease
defaults and continue to provide this service. Here’s a summary of the issues:
default&#xa0;
defaultAll these
default issues ultimately point to an increased spend for the public purse on inappropriate bed and bedfast for vulnerable families.
default&#xa0;
default6.0default&#xa0;default6.1
defaultInnovation to support discharge of duty into PRSdefault&#xa0;defaultThe localism act allows local authorities to discharge the duty of homelessness into the private rented sector. Again we completely support this where families can support themselves. But from our experience there are many families who require 
defaulta higher lev
defaultel of management to help them sustain tenancies. 
defaultExperience also tells us many landlords require extra support to manage vulnerable client groups. Its no secret many private landlords already only accept working families.
